{"timestamp":"2026-07-18T13:30:48.220Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_message","message":"Entire Graph did not inherently emit more model-output tokens. Almost the entire difference came from Claude struggling with the incomplete Zod result.\n\nPer repository:\n\n| Repository | File tools | Entire Graph | Difference |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Chi | 2,356 | **2,124** | Graph −232 |\n| Click | **3,516** | 3,657 | Graph +141 |\n| Zod | **8,709** | 14,208 | Graph +5,499 |\n| Total | 14,581 | 19,989 | Graph +5,408 |\n\nZod accounts for more than 100% of the aggregate gap; Chi partially offsets it.\n\nWhat happened:\n\n1. Graph’s `neighbors` returned only 1 of 7 Zod callers.\n2. Claude explicitly recognized: “The neighbors tool under-reports.”\n3. The benchmark instructions told it to verify or fill Graph gaps with file tools.\n4. Claude therefore performed both workflows:\n   - Graph `search`\n   - Graph `neighbors` twice\n   - seven targeted reads\n   - four greps\n   - additional reasoning to reconcile Graph’s answer with source\n5. That took 20 agent turns versus 16 for file tools and triggered substantially more high-effort hidden reasoning.\n\nClaude’s `output_tokens` include:\n\n- hidden/extended reasoning;\n- generation of tool calls and their arguments;\n- intermediate assistant messages;\n- the structured final answer.\n\nThey do **not** primarily represent text returned by Entire Graph. Graph tool results enter the model as subsequent **input** tokens. If Graph’s response format itself were excessively verbose, we would expect Graph’s provider-input count to be higher—but it was 23% lower overall.\n\nThere is also a smaller harness bias: the Graph treatment mandated at least one `search` and one `neighbors` call, even if one call would have sufficed. Still, Chi used fewer output tokens, demonstrating that the mandatory Graph interaction does not inherently increase output.\n\nSo the accurate conclusion is:\n\n- Entire Graph did not generally cause more output.\n- The tested Zod defect caused Claude to distrust the result, duplicate the investigation using file tools, and spend roughly 5,500 extra output tokens reasoning through the discrepancy.\n- The repaired Graph head should be evaluated with pre-indexing and without a forced redundant verification workflow. File tools should remain available naturally, but the agent should choose whether verification is needed.","phase":"final_answer","memory_citation":null}}
{"timestamp":"2026-07-18T13:30:48.220Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","id":"msg_0bd6d73b974b1fab016a5b800830e08191a6af1d0c2faf9617","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"output_text","text":"Entire Graph did not inherently emit more model-output tokens. Almost the entire difference came from Claude struggling with the incomplete Zod result.\n\nPer repository:\n\n| Repository | File tools | Entire Graph | Difference |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Chi | 2,356 | **2,124** | Graph −232 |\n| Click | **3,516** | 3,657 | Graph +141 |\n| Zod | **8,709** | 14,208 | Graph +5,499 |\n| Total | 14,581 | 19,989 | Graph +5,408 |\n\nZod accounts for more than 100% of the aggregate gap; Chi partially offsets it.\n\nWhat happened:\n\n1. Graph’s `neighbors` returned only 1 of 7 Zod callers.\n2. Claude explicitly recognized: “The neighbors tool under-reports.”\n3. The benchmark instructions told it to verify or fill Graph gaps with file tools.\n4. Claude therefore performed both workflows:\n   - Graph `search`\n   - Graph `neighbors` twice\n   - seven targeted reads\n   - four greps\n   - additional reasoning to reconcile Graph’s answer with source\n5. That took 20 agent turns versus 16 for file tools and triggered substantially more high-effort hidden reasoning.\n\nClaude’s `output_tokens` include:\n\n- hidden/extended reasoning;\n- generation of tool calls and their arguments;\n- intermediate assistant messages;\n- the structured final answer.\n\nThey do **not** primarily represent text returned by Entire Graph. Graph tool results enter the model as subsequent **input** tokens. If Graph’s response format itself were excessively verbose, we would expect Graph’s provider-input count to be higher—but it was 23% lower overall.\n\nThere is also a smaller harness bias: the Graph treatment mandated at least one `search` and one `neighbors` call, even if one call would have sufficed. Still, Chi used fewer output tokens, demonstrating that the mandatory Graph interaction does not inherently increase output.\n\nSo the accurate conclusion is:\n\n- Entire Graph did not generally cause more output.\n- The tested Zod defect caused Claude to distrust the result, duplicate the investigation using file tools, and spend roughly 5,500 extra output tokens reasoning through the discrepancy.\n- The repaired Graph head should be evaluated with pre-indexing and without a forced redundant verification workflow. File tools should remain available naturally, but the agent should choose whether verification is needed."}],"phase":"final_answer","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f756b-4b9e-75e2-8646-c264ec2a1fff"}}}
